Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio.  
Since no non‐current liabilities are separately given, we assume total liabilities equals current liabilities.  
• Total Liabilities = Total Current Liabilities = 378850.51  
• Owner's Equity = 13835266.51  
Debt to Equity Ratio = 378850.51 / 13835266.51 ≈ 0.02738 → Rounded to 0.03  

Step 2: Calculate the Net Profit Margin.  
Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
• Net Profit = 835266.51  
• Total Revenue = 2637011.03  
Net Profit Margin = (835266.51 ÷ 2637011.03) ≈ 0.3168 which is about 31.68%  

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio.  
This ratio = Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities / Total Current Liabilities  
• Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = -1028375.55  
• Total Current Liabilities = 378850.51  
Ratio = -1028375.55 ÷ 378850.51 ≈ -2.7138 → Rounded to -2.71  

Thus, the solution is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.03",
    "Net Profit Margin": "31.68%",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-2.71"
  }
}
